    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Common Questions About Church Ad Templates</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is the best church ad template for Facebook?</h3>
        <p>The best church ad template for Facebook follows the O2F Method structure: a scroll-stopping image or video, a headline that speaks to a felt need, body copy that offers hope without religious jargon, and a clear call to action. Templates that focus on community pain points consistently outperform generic church invitation ads.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How much should a church spend on Facebook ads?</h3>
        <p>Most churches can start seeing results with as little as $5-10 per day. The O2F Method recommends starting with a small budget to test your church ad template, then scaling what works. A $150-300 monthly budget is a strong starting point for most churches looking to reach their community consistently.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What makes a church ad template actually work?</h3>
        <p>A church ad template works when it addresses a real felt need in your community rather than simply promoting your church service. The ad must feel like it belongs in someone's news feed, use authentic imagery, speak the language of your target audience, and include a specific next step like visiting a landing page or attending an event.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Should churches use video or image ads?</h3>
        <p>Both can work, but video ads typically generate more engagement and lower costs per result. A 30-60 second video from your pastor speaking directly to the camera about a community struggle tends to outperform polished graphics. Authenticity beats production quality in church Facebook advertising.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How do I write ad copy for a church ad template?</h3>
        <p>Write ad copy that leads with empathy, not an invitation. Start with the problem your audience faces — loneliness, anxiety, broken relationships — then position your church as a community where people find real answers. Avoid churchy language and write the way real people talk. End with one clear call to action.</p>
      </div>
